**Episode 1.8: The "Model 2" Mystery**  
To conclude the series, the finale must address the "Pivot of 2024-2025."  
 * The Shelved $25k Car: The series reveals that the long-promised "Model 2" (a cheap, $25,000 EV) was largely deprioritized in favor of the Cybercab.  
 * The Robotaxi Bet: Musk’s 2025 declaration that a $25,000 human-driven car is "pointless" serves as the series' final philosophical conflict. It frames Tesla as a company that has moved beyond "driving" to "transportation-as-a-service."

**Episode 1.8 Script Expansion: The "Clean Robotaxi" Debate**  
SCENE START  
[INT. TESLA DESIGN STUDIO - HAWTHORNE, CA - LATE NIGHT (CIRCA 2023/2024)]  
The studio is dark, except for a high-intensity spotlight hitting two clay models. One is a sleek, compact hatchback (the "$25k Model 2"). The other is the CYBERCAB—a low-slung, two-seater with no windows in the back and a sharp, metallic "Cyber" aesthetic.  
FRANZ VON HOLZHAUSEN (56) stands by the hatchback. He looks at ELON MUSK (52), who is pacing, staring at the Cybercab.  
FRANZ  
Elon, we’ve run the numbers. If we build this platform with a steering wheel and pedals first, we can hit the 20-million-car-a-year goal. We can sell it in India, in Europe, in places where the regulations for autonomy are ten years away. It's the 'Global Car.'  
ELON  
(Shaking his head)  
No. No. NO.  
FRANZ  
(Patiently)  
If we go down a path of having no steering wheel, and FSD isn't ready, we won't be able to put them on the road. We’ll have a fleet of sculptures. Let’s make the hardware removable. A 'halfway' car.  
ELON  
(Stops pacing. His voice goes cold)  
I am not designing some sort of amphibian frog. A 'halfway' car is a failure car. If we give the team a steering wheel as a crutch, they’ll use it.  
FRANZ  
It’s not a crutch, it’s a hedge. It’s insurance for the company’s survival.  
ELON  
(Stepping into the light, pointing at the Cybercab)  
This vehicle must be designed as a clean robotaxi. No mirrors. No pedals. No steering wheel. This is me taking responsibility for this decision. It’s my fault if it f--ks up. But we are all in on autonomy.  
[CUT TO: ARCHIVAL FOOTAGE - OCTOBER 2024 "WE, ROBOT" EVENT]  
 * VISUAL: The Cybercab doors swing open—dihedral, supercar-style. The interior is empty of controls. Just a screen.<grok:render card_id="08d01d" card_type="image_card" type="render_searched_image">
<argument name="image_id">9</argument>
<argument name="size">"LARGE"</argument>
</grok:render>  
 * ELON (On Stage): "The cost of autonomous transport will be so low that it will be like individualized mass transit."  
[INT. INTERVIEW - FRANZ VON HOLZHAUSEN (PRESENT DAY 2026)]  
FRANZ  
(Leaning back)  
Elon has this... compulsion for the future. He wants to drag it into the present by its hair. My job is often to be the one saying, 'Wait, we need a way to steer if the computer blinks.' But at a certain point, he just said, 'Clean sheet. No legacy.'  
[INT. ANALYSIS - 2026 MARKET COMMENTARY]  
NARRATOR (V.O.)  
By 2026, that decision remains the ultimate 'all-in' bet. While competitors like BYD flooded the world with cheap, human-driven hatchbacks, Tesla bet its entire volume future on the idea that humans would stop wanting to drive altogether.  
[CLOSE UP: THE CYBERCAB ON A PUBLIC ROAD IN 2026]  
It moves silently through a suburban street. A child in the passenger seat is playing a video game on the center screen. There is no one in the driver's seat.  
NARRATOR (V.O.)  
Is it a revolution? Or a $900 billion gamble that the world is ready to let go of the wheel?  
SCENE END  

**Series Wrap-Up: The Legacy of the Spark**  
The docuseries concludes by showing that Tesla's true product wasn't the car, but the change in expectation. Whether or not the Cybercab succeeds, the "spark" has ensured that no one looks at a gasoline engine the same way again.  
 * Final Stat (2026): Tesla’s FSD fleet surpasses 10 billion miles.  
 * Final Image: A "For Sale" sign on a traditional gas station, being replaced by a Tesla Megapack and a row of V4 Superchargers.

**Key Interviews:** Industry historians, economists, former Tesla executives, and philosophers of technology. A final, reflective piece from an original Roadster owner.